# Relationship Analysis

Common misconceptions:

children may believe:

```text id="p4c1qe"
compare
=
differences
only
```

or:

```text id="u9c6qe"
contrast
=
similarities
```

Some may:

```text id="c3c8qe"
list
random details
```

without understanding:

```text id="k8c5qe"
comparisons
focus on
important ideas
```

Students may also think:

```text id="n1c7qe"
two texts
must be
identical
to compare
```

Example:

students compare:

```text id="t5c3qe"
two animal
articles
```

and answer:

```text id="q2c9qe"
both
have
words
```

instead of recognizing:

```text id="v4c6qe"
both describe habitats
but use
different examples
```

because:

```text id="a6c8qe"
comparison
requires
meaningful relationships
```

This skill teaches:

```text id="g1c4rx"
structured comparison
```

For Grade 5:

focus includes:

Compare:

* similarities
* shared ideas
* common themes
* common structures
* evidence

Contrast:

* differences
* perspectives
* approaches
* structure differences
* author choices

Important idea:

```text id="v5c9rt"
good comparisons
use
important details
```

